# Per-project Cloudflare credentials. Copy to `.env` (gitignored) and fill in.
#
# This exists so you never run `wrangler login` for this repo: that command is GLOBAL and would
# repoint every other project on the machine at this account. See DEPLOYING.md.
#
# Create the token in the account that OWNS the Workers (Admin@spintax.site):
# My Profile → API Tokens → "Edit Cloudflare Workers" template, scoped to that account.
CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=
CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=2a8133f810cef6eff8f7bba2cfd2a09c

# ── Optional: operator credentials, for driving the Bot API from a terminal ──────────────────
#
# Needed ONLY to administer the webhook (getWebhookInfo / setWebhook). Nothing else in this repo
# reads them, and deploying does not require them.
#
# Safe to keep here: `.env` is local-dev + Wrangler's own system environment. It is NOT uploaded
# by `wrangler deploy`, so a value here cannot become a plaintext var in the dashboard and cannot
# clobber the Worker secret of the same name. (Deployed values come from `wrangler secret put` or
# the `vars` key in wrangler.toml — nowhere else.)
#
# Be deliberate about the bot token: it grants full control of the LIVE bot — reading every
# message users send it, sending as it, and repointing the webhook. Rotate with /token at
# @BotFather if it is ever exposed.
#
# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
# TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET=
#
# The WEBHOOK_SECRET must match the Worker secret of the same name, which is not readable back.
# If it was lost, do not try to recover it — set a new value on BOTH sides:
#   printf '%s' "$NEW" | npx wrangler secret put TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET
#   …then pass the same $NEW as `secret_token` in setWebhook (see DEPLOYING.md).
#
# NOTE: a `.dev.vars` file, if present, makes Wrangler ignore `.env` for local dev — so put the
# Worker's own runtime vars in `.dev.vars` (see .dev.vars.example), not both places.
